    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay so if it is nitrogen, how do i fix the soil? do i need to change the pH or just add something to it? also how can i tell if it's actually nitrogen or something else like magnesium?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, you're delving deeper into the garden's mysteries, much like a goblin seeking hidden treasures. If your tomato plants are showing signs of nitrogen deficiency, you can indeed help them by adding a balanced fertilizer that contains nitrogen. This will replenish the nutrients they need to produce lush, green leaves. As for the soil pH, tomatoes prefer a slightly acidic to neutral pH (around 6.0 to 7.0), so testing your soil's pH is a wise move. If it's off, you can adjust it with lime to raise the pH or sulfur to lower it, ensuring your plants have the perfect environment to thrive.\n\nTo distinguish between nitrogen deficiency and other nutrient issues like magnesium, you can look at the symptoms. Nitrogen deficiency typically causes older leaves to turn yellow while the veins remain green, a condition known as chlorosis. Magnesium deficiency, on the other hand, often results in yellowing between the veins of the leaves, starting with the older ones. A soil test can also help pinpoint the exact nutrient deficiencies, guiding you on what to add to your soil to keep your plants happy and healthy, away from any goblin-induced woes.",
